Choosing to do the recommendation system for Yelp Dataset

Two traditional methods:
- Content-based Filtering : 
	Base on the item feature (text, tag, category, embedding)
	Recommend item base on what user liked or preferred
	Cons: Easy to  Over-specialization, hard to explore the new thing
	
- Collaborative Filtering :
	Base on the user behaviors (Rating, click, view,..)
	Recommend item base on what other users  also liked or preferred
	Cons: Cold-start (new user/ new items)
	
Using Hybrid System
Hybrid RS = Content-based + Collaborative Filtering 
(Take advantage of these two method and solve the pros and cons of each other)
There are so many way of combining these two  method together

- *Reduce Cold-Start
- *Personalize better 
- Take advantage of both content and users behaviors

How to Combine them together:
- *Weighted Hybrid (most common)
	Mix score:
	Score = a * score_CBF + (1-a) * score_CF
	
	Easy to implement and often use in production
	E.g: new user (less behavior) -> a high (prioritize content-base method)
		 old user (more behavior) -> a high (prioritize collaborative method)
		 
- *Switching Hybrid
	Choose Content-based or Collaborative method in case:
	
	New user (less behavior) -> Content-based method
	Old users(more behavior) -> Collaborative method
	
	Commonly use to handle cold-start
		
- Cascade Hybrid
	High performance but hard to  implement and complicated
	
- Meta-level hybrid
	Often implement in the big system like YouTube 
	



